[[Image:2006 Clemson at Virginia Tech celebration.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Bowl games are typically a cause for celebration in [[Blacksburg, Virginia|Blacksburg]], [[Virginia]], home of the [[Virginia Tech Hokies]].]]

The list of '''Virginia Tech bowl games''' played since the creation of the [[Virginia Tech football|Virginia Tech Hokies football]] team in 1892 consists of 21&nbsp;post-season [[bowl game]]s. Included in those 21&nbsp;games are three [[Bowl Championship Series]] game appearances and one appearance in the [[BCS National Championship Game|national championship game]]. The Hokies have been invited to a bowl game every year since 1993, a 15-year streak that is surpassed only by Michigan (33&nbsp;games), Florida State (26&nbsp;games), and Florida (17&nbsp;games) for active teams.<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/bowls/current_consecutive.php Current Consecutive Bowl Appearances] College Football Data Warehouse, Accessed [[February 7]], [[2008]].</ref><ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/2007MG/bowl.pdf Orange Bowl Media Guide] Virginia Tech Sports Information, December 2007, Blacksburg, Virginia. Page 4. Accessed [[February 7]], [[2008]].</ref> Including historical streaks, Virginia Tech is tied for eighth with [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Mississippi]] and [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]], who had bowl game streaks during the periods 1957-1971 and 1972-1986, respectively.<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/bowls/alltime_consecutive.php All-Time Consecutive Bowl Appearances] College Football Data Warehouse, Accessed [[February 7]], [[2008]].</ref>

Dozens of [[National Football League]] [[NFL draft|draft picks]] have played for Virginia Tech in bowl games, including two [[List of National Football League first overall draft choices|first-overall selections]]: [[Bruce Smith]] and [[Michael Vick]]. Smith participated in the [[1984 Independence Bowl]], while Vick [[quarterback]]ed the Hokies to their first national championship appearance during the [[2000 Sugar Bowl]], and followed that performance by leading the Hokies to the [[2001 Gator Bowl]], his final collegiate game. Following the game, Vick entered the [[2001 NFL Draft]] and was selected by the [[Atlanta Falcons]].<ref name="Round 1 Atlanta and San Diego">San Diego opted to pass on the No.&nbsp;1 selection, agreeing to a trade with Atlanta Falcons for their No.&nbsp;5 selection. The Falcons took Virginia Tech QB [[Michael Vick]] to begin the 246-player draft. {{cite news
 | title = Atlanta selects QB Vick No. 1 overall
 | work = cnnsi.com
 | publisher = [[CNN]]
 | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/2001/draft/
 | accessdate = 2007-05-04 }}</ref> 

Since 1987, the Virginia Tech football team has been led by head coach [[Frank Beamer]]. Since 1993, Beamer has led the Hokies to 15 consecutive bowl games, going 6&ndash;9 during that period. Beamer has earned [[Paul "Bear" Bryant Award|national coach of the year]] honors several times from various organizations, and has the third-most wins of any active [[Division I]] college football coach.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/staff/beamer.html Frank Beamer] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

Virginia Tech's first post-season bowl game was in 1947, when the Hokies participated in the [[1947 Sun Bowl]] in [[El Paso, Texas]] on [[New Year's Day]] against the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati Bearcats]]. The latest Virginia Tech bowl game occurred on [[January 3]], [[2008]], as the Hokies played the [[2007 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas Jayhawks]] in the [[2008 Orange Bowl]], a Bowl Championship Series game. A loss in that game brought Virginia Tech to an overall bowl record of seven&nbsp;wins and 14&nbsp;losses, putting the Hokies in 55th place in all-time bowl-game winning percentage.<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/bowls/team_records_most_wins.php Most Bowl Wins] College Football Data Warehouse, Accessed [[February 7]], [[2008]].</ref> The Hokies' 21&nbsp;bowl appearances are the 37th-highest total in NCAA history.<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/bowls/team_records_most_bowls.php Team Records - Most Bowl Appearances] College Football Data Warehouse, Accessed [[February 7]], [[2008]].</ref>
