== 1947 Sun Bowl ==
{{main|1947 Sun Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1947 Sun Bowl
|Home=[[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]
|Visitor=Virginia Tech
|Stadium=[[Kidd Field]]
|City=[[El Paso, Texas]]
|Visitor1=0
|Visitor2=0
|Visitor3=0
|Visitor4=6
|Home1=0
|Home2=0
|Home3=12
|Home4=6
|Date=[[January 1]], [[1947]]
}}

The first bowl game in Virginia Tech history came at the conclusion of the 1946 college football season as the Hokies earned a bid to the 1947 [[Sun Bowl]]. The Hokies, led by coach [[James Kitts]], finished the regular season with three losses, three wins, and three ties (3&ndash;3&ndash;3). The team also recorded Virginia Tech's first win over an [[AP Poll|Associated Press]] Top&nbsp;25 team in school history,<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/2004MG/history.pdf The Hokies and the AP Ratings] (PDF) Virginia Tech Sports Information, ''2004 Football Media Guide'' Page 42. Accessed [[December 30]], [[2007]].</ref> the [[Washington and Lee University]] Generals, and the Hokies' traditional rivals, the [[Virginia Military Institute]] Keydets.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/2004MG/history.pdf Year-by-Year Scores and Results] (PDF) "1946", Virginia Tech Sports Information, ''2004 Football Media Guide'' Page 37. Accessed [[December 30]], [[2007]].</ref> Despite those victories, Tech's bid to the Sun Bowl only came about because the bowl's first and second picks had declined the bid and because an influential Tech alumnus on the selection committee had suggested Virginia Tech.<ref>Colston, Chris. ''Tales from the Virginia Tech Sidelines''. Sports Publishing LLC, 2003. Page 26.</ref> Opposing the Hokies were the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati Bearcats]], who had gone 8&ndash;2 during the regular season.<ref>[http://gobearcats.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/year.html Year-by-Year Records] Cincinnati Athletics Department, gobearcats.cstv.com. Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref>

The game [[Kickoff (American football)|kicked off]] on [[January 1]], [[1947]] at at [[Kidd Field]] in [[El Paso, Texas]] in freezing temperatures.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1947Sun.html 1947 Sun Bowl] Virginia Tech Sports Information Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[December 30]], [[2007]].</ref> Defense dominated on both sides in the first half due to the weather and tough play. Neither team scored, but Virginia Tech had the best chance<U+2014>driving to a [[Down (American football)|first down]] inside the Cincinnati two-yard line in the first quarter. The Cincinnati defense held, however, and the game went into [[halftime]] scoreless.

In the second half, the favored Bearcats managed to find success on offense. Behind [[All-American]] Roger Stephens, the Bearcats tallied three&nbsp;[[touchdown]]s to Virginia Tech's one.<ref name="Hokiegames.com">[http://hokiegames.com/blog/2007/12/12/hokie-bowl-20%E2%80%941947-sun-bowl/ Hokie Bowl #20<U+2014>1947 Sun Bowl] The Hokie Games Blog, [[December 17]], [[2007]]. Accessed [[December 30]], [[2007]].</ref> The Hokies managed to block all three Cincinnati [[extra point]] kicks, but without touchdowns of their own, the Hokies had no chance to win. Cincinnati emerged victorious as time ran out, 18&ndash;6.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Cincinnati Virginia Tech Football Opponent Database: Cincinnati] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1966 Liberty Bowl ==
{{main|1966 Liberty Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1966 Liberty Bowl
|Date=[[December 10]], [[1966]]
|Stadium=[[Memphis Memorial Stadium]]
|City=[[Memphis, Tennessee]]
|Visitor=[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=0
|Visitor2=0
|Visitor3=7
|Visitor4=7
|Home1=7
|Home2=0
|Home3=0
|Home4=0
}}

Virginia Tech's second bowl game did not come until nearly 20&nbsp;years after its first. On [[December 10]], [[1966]], the Hokies faced off against the No. 9 [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami Hurricanes]] in the [[Liberty Bowl]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]]. Tech came into the game having gone 8&ndash;1&ndash;1 during [[1966 college football season|the regular season]] under head coach [[Jerry Claiborne]],<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/2007MG/records.pdf Virginia Tech 2007 Football Media Guide] "Year-by-Year Scores and Results", p. 180. Virginia Tech Sports Information Department, Blacksburg Virginia. Accessed [[January 23]], [[2008]].</ref> while the Hurricanes boasted a 7&ndash;2&ndash;1 regular-season record, including wins over [[USC Trojans football|Southern California]] and [[Florida Gators football|Florida]].<ref>[http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mifl/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/06-mg-records 2006 Miami Hurricanes Media Guide] University of Miami Athletics Department, Miami, Florida. Page 145. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> The Hokies were led by [[All-America]] [[Safety (American football)|safety]] [[Frank Loria]], who caught three&nbsp;[[interception]]s and [[punt return|returned]] three&nbsp;[[punt]]s for touchdowns as a [[junior]] during the 1966 season.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/2007MG/records.pdf Virginia Tech 2007 Football Media Guide] "Hokie All-Americans", p. 174. Virginia Tech Sports Information Department, Blacksburg Virginia. Accessed [[January 23]], [[2008]].</ref> On the opposite side of the ball, the Hurricanes were led by All-American Ted Hendricks.<ref name="1966 Liberty Miami Guide">[http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mifl/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/06mpcbowlguide 2006 MPC Computers Bowl Media Guide] University of Miami Athletics Department, Miami, Florida. Page 80. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref>

The game kicked off in frigid {{convert|36|<U+00B0>F|<U+00B0>C|lk=on}} weather,<ref name="1966 Liberty Miami Guide"/> and from the beginning, defense dominated. In the first half, Tech held Miami to just 16&nbsp;yards of [[total offense]],<ref name="1966 Liberty"/> and Miami set bowl game records for fewest rushing yards allowed and fewest first downs allowed.<ref>[http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mifl/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/06mpcbowlguide 2006 MPC Computers Bowl Media Guide] University of Miami Athletics Department, Miami, Florida. Page 74. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> The Hokies got the first big break of the game after blocking Miami's first punt of the game. Taking over at the Miami 21-yard line, it took Virginia Tech just five&nbsp;plays to march into the [[end zone]] for an early 7&ndash;0 lead.<ref name="1966 Liberty">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1966Liberty.html 1966 Liberty Bowl] Virginia Tech Sports Information Department, Blacksburg, Virginia. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> Virginia Tech and Miami battled to a stalemate for the rest of the first half, and Tech went into [[halftime]] still clinging to a 7&ndash;0 lead.

In the second half, Tech's fortune turned. Late in the third quarter, the Virginia Tech defense stopped Miami's offense for yet another time, but instead of receiving the punt cleanly, the Hokies committed a [[American football rules#Fouls against the defense|roughing the kicker penalty]] that allowed Miami to retain possession of the ball with a first down. A few plays later, Miami scored its first touchdown of the game. In the fourth quarter Miami finally took the lead on a 10-play, 70-yard drive.<ref name="1966 Liberty"/> The Hokies were unable to answer the Hurricanes' score, and Miami won the 1966 Liberty Bowl, 14&ndash;7.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Miami Opponent History:Miami] Opponent history database, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[January 23]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1968 Liberty Bowl ==
{{main|1968 Liberty Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1968 Liberty Bowl
|Date=[[December 14]], [[1968]]
|Stadium=[[Memphis Memorial Stadium]]
|City=[[Memphis, Tennessee]]
|Visitor=[[Ole Miss Rebels|Ole Miss]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=0
|Visitor2=14
|Visitor3=7
|Visitor4=13
|Home1=17
|Home2=0
|Home3=0
|Home4=0
}}

Two&nbsp;years after its previous trip to the Liberty Bowl, Virginia Tech was again asked to travel to [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]] to play in a post-season bowl game. This time, the opponent was [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Mississippi]], which had amassed a 6&ndash;3&ndash;1 record during the regular season.<ref>[http://www.olemisssports.com//pdf7/83758.pdf?SPSID=82783&SPID=737&DB_OEM_ID=2600 2007 Ole Miss Media Guide] Mississippi Athletics Department, olemisssports.com. Page 179. Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref> The Hokies came into the game with a 7&ndash;3 record that included a loss to Tech's previous Liberty Bowl opponent, Miami.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1968 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1968-1969] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1968 Liberty Bowl kicked off on [[January 14]], [[1968]]. As in the Hokies' previous Liberty Bowl appearance, Virginia Tech got off to a fast start. On the game's second play, Tech ran 58&nbsp;yards for a touchdown, courtesy of a trick play. After Mississippi fumbled, Tech recovered and scored another quick touchdown. At the end of the first quarter, Tech added a field goal to the two touchdowns it had already earned, making the score 17&ndash;0 at the end of one quarter. From that point onward, however, almost nothing would go in Virginia Tech's favor. Tech attempted an [[onside kick]] following the field goal, but were unable to successfully recover the ball. With good field position following the kick, Mississippi quarterback [[Archie Manning]] orchestrated a 49-yard drive for the Rebels' first points of the game.<ref name="1968 Liberty">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1968Liberty.html 1968 Liberty Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref>

Mississippi scored another touchdown before halftime, and the Hokies clung to a 17&ndash;14 lead at the beginning of the second half. That three-point lead quickly evaporated, however, as 21&nbsp;seconds into the third quarter, Mississippi's Steve Hindman ran for 79&nbsp;yards and a touchdown to give Mississippi a 21&ndash;17 lead.<ref>[http://www.olemisssports.com//pdf7/83758.pdf?SPSID=82783&SPID=737&DB_OEM_ID=2600 2007 Ole Miss Media Guide] Mississippi Athletics Department, olemisssports.com. Page 169. Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref> Ole Miss added 13 more points before the game was over and earned the victory, 34&ndash;17.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Mississippi Virginia Tech Football Opponent History Database: Mississippi] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> The Virginia Tech offense was stymied by repeated turnovers. Tech [[fumble]]d the ball three&nbsp;times and Tech quarterback Humphries threw two&nbsp;interceptions.<ref name="1968 Liberty"/> Tech committed 120&nbsp;yards in penalties and was held to just two&nbsp;passing yards for the entire game.<ref>[http://www.olemisssports.com//pdf7/83758.pdf?SPSID=82783&SPID=737&DB_OEM_ID=2600 2007 Ole Miss Media Guide] Mississippi Athletics Department, olemisssports.com. Page 161. Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1981 Peach Bowl ==
{{main|1981 Peach Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1968 Liberty Bowl
|Date=[[January 2]], [[1981]]
|Stadium=[[Fulton County Stadium]]
|City=[[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]
|Visitor=[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=7
|Visitor2=7
|Visitor3=3
|Visitor4=3
|Home1=0
|Home2=3
|Home3=7
|Home4=0
}}

Following the [[1980 NCAA Division I-A football season|1980 college football season]], Virginia Tech was awarded a bid to the 1981 [[Peach Bowl]] as a reward for finishing 8&ndash;3 during the regular season.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1980 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1980-1981] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing Virginia Tech was a familiar post-season opponent<U+2014>Miami<U+2014>whom the Hokies had played in the 1966 Liberty Bowl. No. 20 Miami finished the regular season with an 8&ndash;3 record.<ref>[http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mifl/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/06-mg-records 2006 Miami Hurricanes Media Guide] University of Miami Athletics Department, Miami, Florida. Page 146. Accessed [[February 22]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1981 Peach Bowl kicked off on [[January 2]], [[1981]] at [[Fulton County Stadium]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. Unlike the 1966 Liberty Bowl, in which Virginia Tech scored first, it was Miami who dominated the game's early going. The Hurricanes scored a touchdown on the first drive of the game and tacked on another touchdown early in the second quarter. Tech was held scoreless in the early going, thanks to two&nbsp;Miami interceptions at the [[goal line]] as Virginia Tech was threatening to score. Late in the second quarter, Tech was finally able to get on the scoreboard with a field goal, but at halftime, the Miami Hurricanes led 14&ndash;3.<ref name="1981 Peach"/>

After halftime, the Hokies threatened Miami for the first time all game. Virginia Tech mounted an 80-yard drive that resulted in a touchdown, cutting Miami's lead to 14&ndash;10. But the Hurricanes' defense clamped down on any further offensive attempts by Virginia Tech and denied the Hokies more points. Miami added two&nbsp;field goals: one in the third quarter and one in the fourth quarter that finally put the game out of reach for Virginia Tech.<ref name="1981 Peach">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1981Peach.html 1981 Peach Bowl] Accessed [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref> Miami earned the win, 20&ndash;10. Miami's win was its first bowl victory since the 1966 Liberty Bowl, which also featured a Hurricanes victory over Virginia Tech.<ref>[http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mifl/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/06mpcbowlguide 2006 MPC Computers Bowl Game Media Guide] University of Miami Athletics Department, Miami, Florida. Page 79. Accessed [[February 22]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1984 Independence Bowl ==
{{main|1984 Independence Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1984 Independence Bowl
|Date=[[December 15]], [[1984]]
|Stadium=[[Independence Stadium]]
|City=[[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]
|Visitor=[[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=3
|Visitor2=7
|Visitor3=0
|Visitor4=13
|Home1=7
|Home2=0
|Home3=0
|Home4=0
}}

The Virginia Tech Hokies earned a bid to the 1984 [[Independence Bowl]] following an 8&ndash;3 record during the [[1984 NCAA Division I-A football season|1984-1985 football season]].<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1984 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1984-1985] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the [[Air Force Falcons football|Falcons]] of the [[United States Air Force Academy]], who had gone 7&ndash;4 during the regular season, including a 5&ndash;3 record in the [[Western Athletic Conference]].<ref>[http://www.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/afa/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/History 2007 Air Force Academy football media guide] Air Force Academy Athletics department, goairforcefalcons.cstv.com. Page 165. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1984 Independence Bowl kicked off on [[December 15]], [[1984]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]. Weather at kickoff was a comfortable {{convert|74|<U+00B0>F|<U+00B0>C|lk=on}} and the wind was from the southwest at {{convert|14|mph|km/h|lk=on}}<U+2013>{{convert|18|mph|km/h|lk=on}}. An estimated 41,100&nbsp;people came out to watch the Falcons take on the Hokies.<ref>[http://www.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/afa/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/History 2007 Air Force Academy football media guide] Air Force Academy Athletics department, goairforcefalcons.cstv.com. Page 169. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref> Air Force scored first with a 35-yard field goal, but the Hokies struck back with a touchdown off of a 10-play, 72-yard drive, putting Virginia Tech ahead 7&ndash;3. That score would remain until halfway through the second quarter, when Virginia Tech [[fumble]]d the ball at its own three-yard line. Air Force recovered the ball and scored a touchdown on the next play, regaining a 10&ndash;7 lead.<ref name="1984 indy">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1984Indep.html 1984 Independence Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref>

At halftime, Air Force still led by 10&ndash;7. Following the half, Virginia Tech's defense began to break down under Air Force's [[Rush (American football)|rush]]ing offense. The Hokies and Air Force battled defensively throughout the third quarter, but in the fourth quarter, Air Force's offense broke free for 13&nbsp;unanswered points.<ref name="1984 indy"/> Tech's offense was stifled by two Air Force interceptions and two&nbsp;lost fumbles, allowing Air Force to earn the easy victory, 23&ndash;7.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Air%20Force Virginia Tech Football Opponent database: Air Force] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1986 Peach Bowl ==
{{main|1986 Peach Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1986 Peach Bowl
|Date=[[December 31]], [[1986]]
|Stadium=[[Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium]]
|City=[[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]]
|Visitor=Virginia Tech
|Home=[[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina State]]
|Visitor1=10
|Visitor2=0
|Visitor3=6
|Visitor4=9
|Home1=7
|Home2=14
|Home3=0
|Home4=3
}}

Virginia Tech's first bowl win in school history came in a dramatic 25&ndash;24 win over the No. 18 [[North Carolina State Wolfpack football|North Carolina State Wolfpack]] in the 1986 Peach Bowl. Tech came into the game with a 9&ndash;1&ndash;1 record that included an unusual forfeit win over [[Temple Owls|Temple]]. The Owls, who had played the game with an ineligible player, won the game on the field, but later forfeited the victory to Virginia Tech.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1986 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1986-1987] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 22]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies in the 1986 Peach Bowl were the 18th-ranked Wolfpack from [[North Carolina State University]]. N.C. State was led by head coach [[Dick Sheridan]] and had a regular-season record of 8&ndash;2&ndash;1 that included five wins over [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] teams.<ref>[http://www.gopack.com/pdf2/80022.pdf?ATCLID=1097536&SPID=3730&DB_OEM_ID=9200&SPSID=41957 2007 NC State football media guide] NC State Athletics Department, Gopack.com. Page 190. Accessed [[February 22]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1986 Peach Bowl kicked off on [[December 31]], [[1986]] at Fulton County Stadium in Atlanta, Georgia,<ref>[http://www.gopack.com/pdf2/80022.pdf?ATCLID=1097536&SPID=3730&DB_OEM_ID=9200&SPSID=41957 2007 NC State football media guide] NC State Athletics Department, Gopack.com. Page 197. Accessed [[February 22]], [[2008]].</ref> five&nbsp;years minus one day since Virginia Tech had last played in Atlanta for the 1981 Peach Bowl. Virginia Tech scored first, but NC State's Bulluck blocked a Tech punt in the Tech end zone and recovered it for a tying touchdown. Virginia Tech kicked a field goal at the end of the quarter to take a 10&ndash;7 lead, but NC State fought back, scoring 14&nbsp;unanswered points in the second quarter to take a 21&ndash;10 lead by halftime.<ref name="1986 Peach">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1986Peach.html 1986 Peach Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 22]], [[2008]].</ref>

In the third quarter, the game turned into a defensive battle. Neither side scored until late in the third quarter, when Tech took advantage of a State fumble to score the first touchdown of the second half. Tech failed to convert a two-point conversion, but NC State fumbled again on the ensuing possession, and Tech was able to drive for another touchdown. Leading 22&ndash;21, Tech attempted another two-point conversion, which also failed.<ref name="1986 Peach"/>

NC State, needing to score, drove down the field and kicked a go-ahead 33-yard field goal with 7:12 remaining in the game. After a failed possession, Tech was forced to ball away, allowing NC State to run down the clock. The Virginia Tech defense eventually forced a stop, giving the Tech offense one final chance to win the game. With 1:53 on the clock and beginning from their own 20-yard line, the Hokies drove 57&nbsp;yards to the NC State 23-yard line. There, kicker Craig Kinzer successfully kicked a 40-yard field goal as time expired to give Virginia Tech a 25&ndash;24 win.<ref name="1986 Peach"/>

== 1993 Independence Bowl ==
{{main|1993 Independence Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1993 Independence Bowl
|Date=[[December 31]], [[1993]]
|Stadium=[[Independence Stadium]]
|City=[[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]
|Visitor=[[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=7
|Visitor2=6
|Visitor3=0
|Visitor4=7
|Home1=7
|Home2=21
|Home3=0
|Home4=17
}}

The No.&nbsp;22 Virginia Tech Hokies came into the 1993 Independence Bowl with a 8&ndash;3 regular-season record that included wins over Pittsburgh and Virginia.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1993 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules, 1993-1994] Hokiesports.com, Accessed [[February 17]], [[2008]].</ref> The bowl appearance was the first for head coach [[Frank Beamer]], who had turned the team around after a 2&ndash;8&ndash;1 season the previous year.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1992 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules, 1992-1993] Hokiesports.com, Accessed [[February 17]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the No. 21 Indiana Hoosiers, who were playing in their first bowl game since the 1991 [[Copper Bowl]].<ref>[http://iuhoosiers.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/ind/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07-bowl-guide-five 2007 Indiana Insight Bowl Guide] Indiana University Athletics Department, Bloomington Indiana, December 2007, Page 68. Accessed [[February 19]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1993 Independence Bowl kicked off on [[December 31]], [[1993]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]. Indiana jumped out to an early lead courtesy of a 75-yard pass from quarterback John Paci. Virginia Tech equalized the score before the first quarter ran out, then took a 14&ndash;7 lead with a second-quarter touchdown run by [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]] Joe Swarm. Indiana climbed back with two field goals that cut Tech's lead to 14&ndash;13. With Indiana in possession of the ball and time running down, it appeared that Indiana would have at least one more attempt on offense before halftime. Before the Indiana drive could get moving, John Paci [[fumble]]d the ball, which was recovered by Virginia Tech and returned 20&nbsp;yards for a touchdown. On Virginia Tech's post-touchdown [[kickoff]], Indiana [[kickoff return|returned]] the ball deep into Virginia Tech territory, setting up a potential field goal by kicker Bill Manolopoulos. During the kick, Virginia Tech defender Jeff Holland broke through the Indiana [[offensive line]] and blocked the field goal attempt.<ref name="1993 indy">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1993Indep.html 1993 Independence Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Blacksburg, Virginia. Accessed [[February 19]], [[2008]].</ref> Tech's [[Antonio Banks]] scooped up the ball and ran 80&nbsp;yards for another touchdown<U+2014>Virginia Tech's second in less than 40&nbsp;seconds.<ref>[http://iuhoosiers.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/ind/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07-bowl-guide-five 2007 Indiana Insight Bowl Guide] Indiana University Athletics Department, Bloomington Indiana, December 2007, Page 69. Accessed [[February 19]], [[2008]].</ref>

The two touchdowns gave Virginia Tech a 28&ndash;13 halftime lead, and Indiana never seriously challenged the Hokies afterward. Both teams failed to score in the fourth quarter, but Virginia Tech added 17&nbsp;points in the fourth quarter to make the game a blowout. Indiana managed a touchdown toward the end of the game, but the end result had already been decided. Virginia Tech won the 1993 Independence Bowl, 45&ndash;20.<ref name="1993 indy"/>

== 1994 Gator Bowl ==
{{main|1994 Gator Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1994 Gator Bowl
|Date=[[December 30]], [[1994]]
|Stadium=[[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium]]
|City=[[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]], [[Florida]]
|Visitor=Virginia Tech
|Home=[[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]]
|Visitor1=0
|Visitor2=10
|Visitor3=6
|Visitor4=7
|Home1=14
|Home2=21
|Home3=0
|Home4=10
}}

The 1994 [[Gator Bowl]] saw 17th-ranked Virginia Tech face off against regional rival [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] at [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium]] on the campus of the [[University of Florida]]. Tech came into the game with an 8&ndash;3 regular-season record that included a record of 5&ndash;2 in [[Big East Conference]] competition.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1994 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1994-1995] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref> The Tennessee Volunteers came entered the game with a regular-season record of 7&ndash;4 under head coach [[Phillip Fulmer]] that included a 5&ndash;3 record in [[Southeastern Conference]] competition.<ref>[http://www.utsports.com/uploadedFiles/Sports/Football/07fb-p124-185.pdf 2007 Tennessee football media guide] Tennessee Athletics Department, [[July 19]], [[2007]]. Page 166. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref>

The game kicked off On [[December 30]], [[1994]] in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]], [[Florida]]. From the start, Tennessee's high-scoring offense dominated. The Volunteers scored two touchdowns in the first quarter and three in the second, while Virginia Tech was able to muster a lone touchdown and field goal in the second quarter. At halftime, Tennessee had a commanding 35&ndash;10 lead.<ref name="1994 Gator">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1994Gator.html 1994 Gator Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref>

The Hokies struggled back in the third quarter, scoring six unanswered points to close the score to 35&ndash;16. In the fourth quarter, however, Tennessee answered Virginia Tech's effort with 10&nbsp;points, putting the game out of reach for the Hokies, who managed only a single touchdown in the fourth quarter.<ref name="1994 Gator"/> The Hokies fumbled the ball five times<U+2014>losing it once<U+2014>and threw two&nbsp;interceptions, allowing Tennessee to cruise to an easy victory, 45&ndash;23. Tennessee [[running back]] James Stewart was named the game's [[most valuable player]].<ref>[http://www.utsports.com/uploads/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/fb-bowls.pdf Tennessee Bowl History] Tennessee Athletics Department, UTsports.com. Accessed [[February 23]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1995 Sugar Bowl ==
{{main|1995 Sugar Bowl (December)}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=1995 Sugar Bowl
|Date=[[December 31]], [[1995]]
|Stadium=[[Louisiana Superdome ]]
|City=[[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]
|Visitor=Virginia Tech
|Home={{cfb link|year=1995|team=Texas Longhorns|title=Texas}}
|Visitor1=0
|Visitor2=7
|Visitor3=7
|Visitor4=14
|Home1=7
|Home2=3
|Home3=0
|Home4=0
}}

In 1995, Virginia Tech received its first bid to a [[Bowl Coalition]] game. The Bowl Coalition, predecessor to the modern [[Bowl Championship Series]], was intended to match up the two best teams in the [[Sugar Bowl|Sugar]], [[Orange Bowl (game)|Orange]], [[Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta]], and [[Rose Bowl]]s, with the two highest-ranked teams playing in a [[NCAA Division I-A national football championship|National Championship Game]]. Following the [[1995 NCAA Division I-A football season|1995-1996 college football season]], Virginia Tech was selected to play in the 1995 Sugar Bowl as a result of this coalition. The No. 13 Hokies, who finished 9&ndash;2 during the regular season and were named [[Big East Conference]] champions,<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1995 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1995-1996] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 24]], [[2008]].</ref> played against the No. 9 [[Texas Longhorns football|University of Texas]], who finished 10&ndash;1&ndash;1 during the regular season en route to becoming [[Southwest Conference]] champions.<ref>[http://www.mackbrown-texasfootball.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=36&url_subchannel_id=&url_article_id=1349&change_well_id=2 Texas football All-Time results] University of Texas Athletics department, Mackbrown-texasfootball.com. Accessed [[February 24]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1995 Sugar Bowl kicked off on [[December 31]], [[1995]] in the [[Louisiana Superdome]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]. Defense dominated in the first quarter as neither team scored during the game's first four&nbsp;possessions. Late in the quarter, however, Texas' offense, led by quarterback James Brown, put together an eight-play, 72-yard drive that ended with a four-yard [[touchdown]] [[forward pass|pass]]. At the end of the first quarter, Texas led 7&ndash;0.<ref>[http://www.mackbrown-texasfootball.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=36&url_subchannel_id=&url_article_id=752&change_well_id=2 1995 Sugar Bowl: Virginia Tech 28, Texas 10] University of Texas Athletics department, Mackbrown-texasfootball.com. Accessed [[February 24]], [[2008]].</ref> Early in the second quarter, Texas added another three points with a 52-yard field goal that came off of an interception. But the Hokies began to fight back. Brian Still returned a Texas punt 60&nbsp;yards for Tech's first points of the game, and at halftime, the Longhorns' lead was cut to just three&nbsp;points.<ref name="1995 Sugar"/>

In the second half, Virginia Tech's defense kicked into high gear. Cornell Brown, the Hokies' [[All-American]] [[defensive end]], was a key player as Tech [[quarterback sack|sacked]] the Texas quarterback five&nbsp;times and caught three&nbsp;pass [[interception]]s. On offense, [[wide receiver]] Brian Still added two&nbsp;passing touchdowns to his punt return touchdown, and the Hokies scored 21&nbsp;unanswered points in the second half.<ref name="1995 Sugar">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1995Sugar.html 1995 Sugar Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 24]], [[2008]].</ref> Tech won the game, 28&ndash;10. The win was the third&nbsp;bowl victory in school history, and was by far the highest-profile win for the school at the time.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Texas Virginia Tech Football Opponent History: Texas] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 24]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1996 Orange Bowl ==
<!-- Note: there were two 1996 Orange Bowls - one played on January 1, 1996, following the 1995 season, and the other played on December 31, 1996, following the 1996 season.  This section is about the latter.  See http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1996Orange.html -->
{{main|1996 Orange Bowl (December)}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
 |Name=1996 Orange Bowl<ref>There were two 1996 Orange Bowls - [[1996 Orange Bowl|the first]] played on [[January 1]], [[1996]], following the 1995 season, and the other played on December 31, 1996, following the 1996 season.  Virginia Tech played in the latter.</ref>
 |Date=[[December 31]], [[1996]]
 |Visitor=Virginia Tech
 |Visitor1=7
 |Visitor2=7
 |Visitor3=7
 |Visitor4=0
 |Home=[[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]
 |Home1=0
 |Home2=17
 |Home3=14
 |Home4=10
 |Stadium=[[Pro Player Stadium]]
 |City=[[Miami Gardens, Florida]]
}}

A year after earning a bid to its first Bowl Coalition game, Tech again earned the honor of participating in an upper-tier bowl game. Under the newly-renamed [[Bowl Alliance]], Virginia Tech was selected to play in the 1996 [[Orange Bowl]]. The No. 10 Hokies finished 10&ndash;1 in the regular season, en route to their second consecutive [[Big East Conference]] championship.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1996 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1996-1997] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the No. 6 [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska Cornhuskers]], who had finished 10&ndash;2 during the [[1996 NCAA Division I-A football season|1996-1997 season]], including a loss to [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] in the [[Big 12 Conference]] championship game.<ref>[http://www.huskers.com//pdf6/79418.pdf?ATCLID=2722&SPSID=8&SPID=22&DB_OEM_ID=100 Nebraska All-Time results: 1955-1997] Nebraska Athletics department, Huskers.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1996 Orange Bowl kicked off on [[December 31]], [[1996]], exactly one year after the Hokies' previous bowl game. Instead of [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], however, the Hokies were playing in stormy [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Florida]] at [[Pro Player Stadium]]. Neither team scored until late in the first quarter when Tech quarterback [[Jim Druckenmiller]] put Virginia Tech on the board with a 19-yard touchdown pass. The Hokies' 7&ndash;0 lead at the end of the first quarter didn't last long, however. Nebraska scored a field goal early in the second quarter and tacked on a touchdown to take a 10&ndash;7 lead halfway through the second quarter. Then Nebraska got its biggest play of the game as Tech's Druckenmiller [[fumble]]d the ball. A Nebraska player scooped up the ball, returning it 31&nbsp;yards for a touchdown. Tech was able to score a touchdown before halftime, but Nebraska still held a 17&ndash;14 lead as the second half began.<ref name="96 Orange">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1996Orange.html 1996 Orange Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

Nebraska widened its lead with a 33-yard touchdown run six minutes into the second half, but Tech answered right back with a 33-yard touchdown pass on its subsequent possession. The score cut Nebraska's lead to 24&ndash;21. Unfortunately for the Hokies, that score was the closest they would get to a lead as Nebraska's offense began to wear down the Tech defense.<ref name="96 Orange"/> Nebraska scored another touchdown in the fourth quarter, then racked up 10&nbsp;points in the fourth quarter to secure the victory. Nebraska won, 41&ndash;21.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Nebraska Virginia Tech Football Opponent Database: Nebraska] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1998 Gator Bowl ==
{{main|1998 Gator Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
 |Name=1998 Gator Bowl
 |Date=[[January 1]], [[1998]]
 |Visitor=Virginia Tech
 |Visitor1=0
 |Visitor2=0
 |Visitor3=3
 |Visitor4=0
 |Home=[[North Carolina Tarheels football|North Carolina]]
 |Home1=16
 |Home2=6
 |Home3=6
 |Home4=14
 |Stadium=[[Alltel Stadium]]
 |City=[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida|FL]]
}}

Following the [[1997 NCAA Division I-A football season|1997 college football season]], Virginia Tech was selected to play in the 1998 Gator Bowl as a reward for a 7&ndash;4 regular season.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1997 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules, 1997-1998] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com, Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the unranked Hokies were the No.&nbsp;7-ranked [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina Tar Heels]]. The Heels had gone 10&ndash;1 during the regular season and were ranked seventh in the [[AP Poll|Associated Press poll]] heading into the game. North Carolina was playing under new head coach [[Carl Torbush]] for the first time. Torbush had taken over for former head coach [[Mack Brown]] on [[December 8]] after Brown announced that he was departing to take the position of head coach at [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]].<ref name="UNC media guide"/>

The game kicked off on [[January 1]], [[1998]] at [[Alltel Stadium]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]]. From the opening kickoff, North Carolina dominated every aspect of the game. In the first quarter, the Tar Heels scored 16&nbsp;points, matching the total number of first-quarter points they had scored in every game of the regular season combined.<ref name="UNC media guide">[http://www.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/unc/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history121-156 2007 North Carolina football media guide] North Carolina Athletics Department, Tarheelblue.cstv.com. Page 143. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2005]].</ref> North Carolina added six points in the second and third quarters before Tech scored its first points of the game<U+2014>a 40-yard [[field goal]] by kicker [[Shayne Graham]]. North Carolina set records for largest bowl game margin of victory, most points scored in a bowl game, and most touchdown passes in a bowl game.<ref name="UNC media guide"/>

The eventual 42&ndash;3 loss was Virginia Tech's largest bowl loss in school history.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1998Gator.html 1998 Gator Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com, Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 1998 Music City Bowl ==
{{main|1998 Music City Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
 |Name=1998 Music City Bowl
 |Date=[[December 29]], [[1998]]
 |Visitor=Virginia Tech
 |Visitor1=7
 |Visitor2=3
 |Visitor3=14
 |Visitor4=14
 |Home=[[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]
 |Home1=0
 |Home2=7
 |Home3=0
 |Home4=0
 |Stadium=[[Vanderbilt Stadium]]
 |City=[[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]]
}}

Virginia Tech's 8&ndash;3 record during the 1998 college football regular season was good enough to earn it a bid to the inaugural [[Music City Bowl]] game.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=1998 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 1998-1999] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama Crimson Tide]], who had gone 7&ndash;4 during the regular season.<ref>[http://www.rolltide.com/SportSelect.dbml?&SPSID=37427&SPID=3011&DB_OEM_ID=8000&Q_SEASON=1998 Alabama Football - 1998 Schedule & Results] Alabama Athletics department, Rolltide.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 1998 Music City Bowl kicked off on [[December 29]], [[1998]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]]. The weather at kickoff was "horrid," as rain and [[sleet]] mixed in freezing temperatures.<ref>[https://admin.xosn.com/fls/8000/files/football/2007/bowlguide/102-124.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=8000 2007 Alabama Bowl Guide] Alabama Athletics department, Rolltide.com. Page 123. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref> The game's early going was marked by defense as both teams struggled against the inclement weather. Virginia Tech scored first off of a 43-yard [[touchdown]] [[scramble]] by quarterback Al Clark. Clark's touchdown provided the game's only points until the second quarter, when Alabama evened the score at 7&ndash;7 with a five-yard touchdown pass. The Hokies struck back with a [[field goal]] before [[halftime]] and took a tenuous 10&ndash;7 lead into the second half.<ref name="1998 MCB">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/1998Music.html 1998 Music City Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

In that half, the Tech offense finally got rolling. The Hokies scored 14&nbsp;points in both the third and fourth quarters, ending the game on an uncontested 28&ndash;0 run. Alabama's offense was stifled throughout by effective pressure from Tech [[defensive end]] [[Corey Moore]], and Tech was able to turn several [[fumble]]s and [[interceptions]] by the Crimson Tide into points on the scoreboard. The final 38&ndash;7 Virginia Tech victory was the biggest win in Virginia Tech bowl game history.<ref name="1998 MCB"/>

== 2000 Sugar Bowl ==
{{main|2000 BCS National Championship Game}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
 |Name=2000 Sugar Bowl
 |Date=[[January 4]], [[2000]]
 |Visitor=[[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]
 |Visitor1=14
 |Visitor2=14
 |Visitor3=0
 |Visitor4=18
 |Home = Virginia Tech
 |Home1=7
 |Home2=7
 |Home3=15
 |Home4=0
 |Stadium=[[Louisiana Superdome]]
 |City=[[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]
}}

In their first trip to a bowl sponsored by the newly formed [[Bowl Championship Series]]<U+2014>which had replaced the [[Bowl Alliance]]<U+2014>the No. 2 Hokies returned to [[New Orleans]] to face [[Bobby Bowden]]'s No. 1 [[1999 Florida State Seminoles football team]] for the [[NCAA Division I-A national football championship|national championship]]. The Seminoles had narrowly lost the [[1999 BCS National Championship Game]] to the [[1998 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee Volunteers]] and were looking to polish off an undefeated season by beating Virginia Tech.

The Hokies' offense starred [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] freshman [[quarterback]] [[Michael Vick]], who finished the season as the third-place runner-up for the [[Heisman Trophy]].<ref name=hokiesprofile>{{cite web |title=Vick's Hokies profile |work=hokiesports.com |url=http://www.hokiesports.com/vick/ |accessdate=2007-08-31}}</ref> Vick's Hokies, who had been favored in every game that year, entered the game as 5.5-point underdogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covers.com/pageLoader/pageLoader.aspx?page=/data/ncf/teams/pastresults/1999-2000/team45.html|title=Virginia Tech Hokies 1999 Results|publisher=covers.com|accessdate=2008-02-13}}</ref>

The game kicked off on [[January 4]], [[2000]] in the [[Louisiana Superdome]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].
Florida State jumped out to a quick 28&ndash;7 lead in the first two quarters of play, but the Hokies closed the lead to a 28&ndash;14 margin by halftime with a 3-yard run from Vick. In the second half, Tech made its biggest run of the game as Kicker [[Shayne Graham]] kicked a field goal and tailback Andre Kendrick added two rushing touchdowns to give the Hokies their first and only lead&mdash;29&ndash;28&mdash;with just over three minutes left in the third quarter.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/2000Sugar.html 2000 Sugar Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref> But in the end, the Hokies could not contain Florida State quarterback [[Chris Weinke]], who threw two&nbsp;touchdowns in the fourth quarter and 329&nbsp;yards in the game. The Seminoles defeated Virginia Tech 46&ndash;29.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores100/100004/100004350.htm|date=2000-01-04|title=Virginia Tech vs. Florida State|accessdate=2008-02-13|publisher=USA Today}}</ref>

== 2001 Gator Bowl ==
{{main|2001 Gator Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=2001 Gator Bowl
|Date=[[January 1]], [[2001]]
|Stadium=[[Alltel Stadium]]
|City=[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]]
|Visitor=[[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=0
|Visitor2=10
|Visitor3=3
|Visitor4=7
|Home1=14
|Home2=7
|Home3=13
|Home4=7
}}

After the Hokies' participation in the [[2000 BCS National Championship Game]], the Virginia Tech entered the [[2000 NCAA Division I-A football season|2000-2001 college football season]] with high expectations. Until late in the season, those hopes were borne out, and it appeared as if the Hokies would return to the national championship game. After a late-season loss to No.&nbsp;3-ranked Miami, however, Tech was knocked out of contention for the national title. Following the conclusion of its 10&ndash;1 season, No. 6 Tech was selected to participate in the Gator Bowl.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=2000 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 2000-2001] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the No. 16 Clemson Tigers, who had finished 9&ndash;2 during the regular season.<ref>[http://clemsontigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/clem-m-footbl-2000-res.html Clemson Tigers football: 2000-01 Results] Clemson Athletics department, Clemsontigers.cstv.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 2001 Gator Bowl kicked off on [[January 1]], [[2001]] at [[Alltel Stadium]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]]. <ref>[http://clemsontigers.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/clem/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/bowl_guide_065-128 2007 Chick-fil-A Media Guide] Clemson Athletics department, Clemsontigers.cstv.com. Page 99. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref> Early on, Virginia Tech took advantage of Clemson mistakes to build a first-quarter lead. On the game's first possession, the Tech defense forced a Clemson [[punt]]. Clemson mishandled the kick, and Tech was able to recover the ball at the Clemson 23-yard line. One play later, Tech was on the board with a [[touchdown]] [[forward pass|pass]] from [[quarterback]] [[Michael Vick]]. By the end of the first quarter, Tech had taken a 14&ndash;0 lead. Clemson was able to close the gap to 14&ndash;10 in the second quarter, but Tech added another touchdown before [[halftime]] to take a 21&ndash;10 lead into the second half.<ref name="2001 Gator">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/2001Gator.html 2001 Gator Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

In that half, Tech pulled steadily away from the Tigers. Virginia Tech scored 13&nbsp;points in the third quarter and seven in the fourth quarter, and Clemson never seriously challenged the Hokies, who went on to record a 41&ndash;20 victory.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Clemson Virginia Tech Football Opponent History: Clemson] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref> The game was the final collegiate contest for Tech quarterback Michael Vick, who would go on to be selected as the first overall pick in the [[2001 NFL Draft]].<ref name="2001 Gator"/>

== 2002 Gator Bowl ==
{{main|2002 Gator Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=2002 Gator Bowl
|Year=2002
|Type=bg
|Image=
|Date=[[January 1]], [[2002]]
|Stadium=[[Alltel Stadium]]
|City=[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]]
|Visitor=[[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=0
|Visitor2=10
|Visitor3=3
|Visitor4=17
|Home1=3
|Home2=0
|Home3=14
|Home4=0
}}

No. 15 Virginia Tech was selected to play in the 2002 Gator Bowl with an 8&ndash;3 [[2001 NCAA Division I-A football season|regular-season]] record despite having just played in Jacksonville at the end of the previous year.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=2001 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 2001-2002] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 27]], [[2008]].</ref> The selection of Virginia Tech over the [[Syracuse Orange football|Syracuse Orangemen]] (now just the "Orange") despite losing head-to-head and Syracuse having better conference and overall records was controversial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/112806/spo_6495905.shtml|title=ACC rule affects bowl pick|date=2006-11-28|last=Smits|first=Gary|accessdate=2008-02-17|publisher=The Florida Times-Union}}</ref>  No. 24 [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]], who had failed to win at least a share of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] title for the first time since joining the league in 1992, and who had played in all three [[BCS National Championship]] games held to that point, was selected as the opponent.

The 2002 Gator Bowl kicked off on [[January 1]], [[2002]] at Alltel Stadium in Jacksonville, Florida, exactly one year since the Hokies had last played in the game. The game's early going seemed promising for the defense-minded Hokies. In the first quarter, Tech held Florida State scoreless despite only managing a single field goal on offense. In the third quarter, however, Florida State began to find gaps in the Hokie defense and scored 10&nbsp;points. At halftime, Florida State held a 10&ndash;3 lead.<ref name="02 Gator">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/2002Gator.html 2002 Gator Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 27]], [[2008]].</ref>

In the third quarter, Tech struck back. The Hokies scored 14&nbsp;points in the quarter, while Florida State managed just a field goal. 
The Hokies' All-American tailback [[Lee Suggs]] had suffered a season-ending injury in the first game of the season, but freshman [[Kevin Jones (American football)|Kevin Jones]] had carried the offense for the season, and continued to perform well in the post-season Gator Bowl game. With a 5-yard run from Jones and a 55-yard pass from [[Grant Noel]] to [[Andr<U+00E9> Davis]], Tech took a 17&ndash;13 lead going into the fourth quarter. But the lead quickly evaporated on a 77-yard catch and run from [[Chris Rix]] to [[Javon Walker]].<ref name="02 Gator"/>

Florida State added ten more points after the long touchdown pass, and the Seminoles went on to win the game, 30&ndash;17.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/opponents.html?opponent=Florida%20State Virginia Tech Football Opponent History: Florida State] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 27]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 2002 San Francisco Bowl ==
{{main|2002 San Francisco Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=2002 San Francisco Bowl
|Year=2002
|Date=[[December 31]], [[2002]]
|Stadium=[[Pacific Bell Park]]
|City=[[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[California]]
|Visitor=[[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=10
|Visitor2=0
|Visitor3=0
|Visitor4=3
|Home1=7
|Home2=3
|Home3=7
|Home4=3
}}

No. 21 Virginia Tech was selected for the inaugural edition of the [[San Francisco Bowl]] after an 9&ndash;4 record during the [[2002 NCAA Division I-A football season|2002 college football season]].<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=2002 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 2002-2003] Virginia Tech athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the [[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force Academy Falcons]], who received their bid following an 8&ndash;4 regular season.<ref>[http://goairforcefalcons.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/afa-m-footbl-sched-2002.html 2002 Air Force Academy Falcons football team] Air Force athletics department, Goairforcefalcons.cstv.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 2002 San Francisco Bowl kicked off on [[December 31]], [[2002]] at [[Pacific Bell Park]] in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[California]]. The weather was clear and unseasonably warm for San Francisco in late December, but the field was soggy after several days of rain.<ref name="02 San Fran AP">[http://goairforcefalcons.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/123102aaa.html Falcons Lose Inaugural San Francisco Bowl To Hokies] Greg Beacham, The Associated Press. Goairforcefalcons.cstv.com. [[January 1]], [[2003]]. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref> In the first seven minutes of the game, Air Force scored 10&nbsp;consecutive points to take an early 10&ndash;0 lead. The Tech defense eventually clamped down on the Falcons' offense, however, and only allowed three points for the remainder of the game. The Virginia Tech offense slowly climbed back from the initial 10-point deficit, scoring a [[touchdown]] in the first quarter and a [[field goal]] in the second. By [[halftime]], the Hokies had equalized the score at 10&ndash;10.<ref name="02 Sanfran">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/2002SanFran.html 2002 San Fransisco Bowl] Virginia Tech athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

In the second half, defense continued to dominate as Tech built a lead. The Hokies scored the only points of a third quarter as [[running back]] [[Lee Suggs]] ran into the [[end zone]] from one yard out, allowing Tech to take a 17&ndash;10 lead into the fourth quarter. The Falcons didn't give up easily, however. Air Force kicker Joey Ashcroft cut into the Tech lead with a 21-yard field goal. Tech matched the score later in the quarter to restore the one-touchdown lead. As time ran down, Air Force had one final chance to tie the game and send it into [[overtime]]. Beginning at its own 18-yard line with 4:11 left to play, the Falcons drove deep into Tech territory. With seven seconds remaining, Air Force quarterback Chance Harridge tried to [[scramble]] into the [[end zone]], but was stopped before the [[goal line]] by Tech [[cornerback]] Ronyell Whitaker. The defensive stop preserved the 20&ndash;13 Hokie victory, and Tech quarterback Bryan Randall was named the game's [[most valuable player]].<ref name="02 Sanfran"/>

== 2003 Insight Bowl ==
{{main|2003 Insight Bowl}}
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=2003 Insight Bowl
|Year=2003
|Date=[[December 26]], [[2003]]
|Stadium=[[Bank One Ballpark]]
|City=[[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]]
|Visitor=[[California Golden Bears football|California]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=7
|Visitor2=14
|Visitor3=21
|Visitor4=10
|Home1=21
|Home2=7
|Home3=0
|Home4=21
}}

During the latter half of the [[2003 NCAA Division I-A football season|2003 college football season]], Virginia Tech struggled. Following an 8&ndash;4 regular season, that saw the Hokies lose four of its last six&nbsp;regular-season games, Tech accepted a bid to the 2003 [[Insight Bowl]].<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=2003 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 2003-2004] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the [[California Golden Bears football|California Golden Bears]], who had gone 7&ndash;6 during the regular season, tying for third place in the [[Pacific 10]].<ref>[http://calbears.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/cal/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/g-FB1to11-121003 2003 California Golden Bears Insight Bowl Media Guide] California Athletics department, Calbears.cstv.com. Page 1. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 2003 Insight Bowl kicked off on [[December 26]], [[2003]] at [[Bank One Ballpark]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]]. From the beginning, it was a quick-paced, high-scoring game. In the first quarter, Virginia Tech jumped out to a 21&ndash;7 lead courtesy of the Tech passing game, which saw quarterback [[Bryan Randall]] eventually throw four touchdowns. In the second quarter, California partially recovered from its 14-point first-quarter deficit by scoring two&nbsp;touchdowns. Tech, meanwhile, scored another, and took a 28&ndash;21 lead into halftime.<ref name="2003 Insight">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/2003Insight.html 2003 Insight Bowl] Virginia Tech Athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

The offensive onslaught continued in the second half, though it was California that took the advantage at first. Bolstered by an improved defensive effort that held the Hokies scoreless throughout the third quarter, California, behind quarterback [[Aaron Rodgers]], scored 21 unanswered points to take a 42&ndash;28 lead into the fourth quarter. But in that quarter, the Hokies clawed back into competition. Tech scored a touchdown to begin the quarter, but Cal answered right back with one of its own, making the score 49&ndash;35. The Hokies then evened the score at 49&ndash;49 after an 80-yard drive that took less than two minutes and a punt return by DeAngelo Hall for a touchdown.<ref name="2003 Insight"/> With time running out, Cal still had a chance to drive for a game-winning score. The post-score Tech kickoff went out of bounds, giving the Bears possession at their 35-yard line. Cal needed just seven&nbsp;plays to march 47&nbsp;yards to set up the game-winning field goal. As time expired, kicker Tyler Frederickson kicked a 35-yard field goal try to give California the 52&ndash;49 win.<ref>[http://calbears.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/cal/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07-post-5 2007 California Golden Bears football Media Guide] California Athletics department, Calbears.cstv.com. Pages 69-70. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 2005 Sugar Bowl ==
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
 |Name=2005 Sugar Bowl
 |Date=[[January 3]], [[2005]]
 |Visitor=Virginia Tech
 |Visitor1=0
 |Visitor2=0
 |Visitor3=0
 |Visitor4=13
 |Home=[[2004 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]
 |Home1=6
 |Home2=3
 |Home3=7
 |Home4=0
 |Type=bg
 |Stadium=[[Louisiana Superdome]]
 |City=[[New Orleans, Louisiana]]
}}
{{main|2005 Sugar Bowl}}
{{seealso|2004 Virginia Tech Hokies football team}}

A decade after Virginia Tech's selection the 1995 Sugar Bowl and five years after its appearance in a Sugar Bowl game that served as the national championship game, Tech was again selected to play in New Orleans' annual Sugar Bowl game. The No. 9 Hokies finished the regular season 10&ndash;2 and won the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] championship their first year in the conference, winning an automatic bid to the game.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=2004 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules: 2004-2005] Virginia Tech athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref> Facing the Hokies were the No. 3 [[Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]], who had gone 12&ndash;0 during the regular season.<ref>[http://auburntigers.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/aub/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07-mg-history 2007 Auburn football media guide] Auburn University athletics department, Auburntigers.cstv.com. Page 147. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref> Normally, Auburn's undefeated season would have been justification for a spot in the [[2005 BCS National Championship Game]], but because two other teams had also gone undefeated during the regular season, Auburn, as the No. 3 team in the country, was left out of the National Championship game.<ref>[http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/6783376/site/21683474/ Auburn holds off Virginia Tech in Sugar Bowl] The Associated Press, MSNBC.com. [[January 4]], [[2005]]. Accessed Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

[[Image:Superdome Sunset.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The [[Louisiana Superdome]] was the site of the 2005 Sugar Bowl]]
The 2005 Sugar Bowl kicked off at the [[Louisiana Superdome]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]] on [[January 3]], [[2005]]. The game's early going was marked by defense and field goals. Virginia Tech didn't score in the first half, and Auburn managed just three&nbsp;field goals, including one taken inside the Virginia Tech [[red zone]] after Auburn failed to score a touchdown from the Tech one-yard line. Tech also had a chance to score a touchdown from inside their opponent's one-yard line, but like Auburn, failed to do so. The Hokies elected to try for a touchdown rather than a field goal on [[Down (American football)|fourth down]], but were stopped. At halftime, Auburn had a 9&ndash;0 lead.<ref name="2005 Sugar">[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/2005Sugar.html 2005 Nokia Sugar Bowl] Virginia Tech athletics department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

In the second half, both teams had more offensive success. Auburn scored the game's first touchdown four and a half minutes into the third quarter, widening the Tigers' lead to 16&ndash;0. Virginia Tech fought back, driving inside the Auburn 10-yard line before settling for a field goal attempt. Kicker Brandon Pace missed the 23-yard field goal try, leaving the score at 16&ndash;0. Tech would have other chances, however. With less than seven minutes remaining in the game, Tech scored its first points of the game after a six-play, 78-yard drive. A 29-yard touchdown pass from quarterback Bryan Randall made the score 16&ndash;6 after a missed [[two-point conversion]]. As time ran down, Tech closed the gap even further. With just over two&nbsp;minutes remaining in the game, Randall connected on an 80-yard pass to wide receiver Josh Morgan for a touchdown. With the score now at 16&ndash;13 and time running out, Tech elected to attempt an [[onside kick]] in hopes of having a chance for a game-winning offensive drive. Auburn recovered the kick, however, and ran out the clock.<ref name="2005 Sugar"/> 

Auburn won the game, 16&ndash;13, and Auburn quarterback Jason Campbell was named the game's most valuable player.<ref>[http://auburntigers.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/aub/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07-mg-history 2007 Auburn football media guide] Auburn University athletics department, Auburntigers.cstv.com. Page 153. Accessed [[February 25]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 2006 Gator Bowl ==
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=2006 Gator Bowl
|Date=[[January 2]], [[2006]]
|Stadium=[[Alltel Stadium]]
|City=[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]]
|Visitor=Virginia Tech
|Home=[[2005 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]]
|Visitor1=3
|Visitor2=7
|Visitor3=3
|Visitor4=22
|Home1=14
|Home2=3
|Home3=0
|Home4=7
}}
{{main|2006 Gator Bowl}}
{{seealso|2005 Virginia Tech Hokies football team}}

Virginia Tech was selected as a participant in the 2006 Gator Bowl following a 10&ndash;2 regular season that included wins over 15th-ranked [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]] and traditional rivals [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia]].<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/pastschedules.html?season=2005 Virginia Tech Football Past Schedules] Virginia Tech Athletics Department, Blacksburg, Virginia. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> A loss to [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] in the [[2005 ACC Championship Game|inaugural ACC Championship Game]] had given Tech a bid to the Gator Bowl instead of the more prestigious [[Bowl Championship Series]]-run [[2006 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] game. Facing the 12th-ranked Hokies were the 15th-ranked [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville Cardinals]], who had gone 9&ndash;2 during their first season in the [[Big East Conference]].<ref>[http://uoflsports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120405aab.html Cards Will Face Virginia Tech in 61st Toyota Gator Bowl] Louisville Athletics Department, Louisville, Kentucky. [[December 4]], [[2005]]. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> Louisville had won its last five games before the Gator Bowl and had participated in the [[Liberty Bowl]] during the previous season.<ref>[http://uoflsports.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/lou/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/06gatorbowlguide 2006 Gator Bowl Media Guide] Louisville Athletics Department, Louisville, Kentucky. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref>

The 2006 Gator Bowl was played on [[January 2]], [[2006]] at 12:30 p.m. [[Eastern Standard Time|EST]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=260020259 Vick powers second-half rally as Hokies win Gator Bowl] The Associated Press, ESPN.com, [[January 2]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> Louisville led for much of the game, beginning with an 11-yard touchdown pass in the first quarter by quarterback Hunter Cantwell. Tech was only able to answer with a field goal while Louisville was able to add another touchdown before the end of the quarter.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=260020259&period=1 2006 Gator Bowl:1st Qtr Play-by-Play] ESPN.com, [[January 2]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> In the second quarter, Virginia Tech fought back and narrowed Louisville's lead to a single touchdown. At halftime, the score was 17&ndash;10 in Louisville's favor.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=260020259&period=2 2006 Gator Bowl:2nd Qtr Play-by-Play] ESPN.com, [[January 2]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref>

In the second half, Virginia Tech's offense began to have success. Tech earned the only points of the third quarter<U+2014>a 28-yard field goal from kicker Brandon Pace<U+2014>to narrow Louisville's lead to 17&ndash;13.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=260020259&period=3 2006 Gator Bowl:3rd Qtr Play-by-Play] ESPN.com, [[January 2]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> In the fourth quarter, however, the game fully turned in the Hokies' favor. Though Louisville scored a touchdown early in the quarter, the Hokies' scored 22&nbsp;unanswered points in the final 13 minutes of the game to take a 35&ndash;24 lead and earn the win.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=260020259&period=4 2006 Gator Bowl:4th Qtr Play-by-Play] ESPN.com, [[January 2]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref>

The Hokie win was marred by excessive penalties and unsportsmanlike conduct that resulted in the ejection of one&nbsp;player.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/football/bowls/2006Gator.html 2006 Toyota Gator Bowl] Virginia Tech Sports Information Department, Hokiesports.com. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> Following the game, Virginia Tech quarterback [[Marcus Vick]] was released from the team as a result of several incidents of misconduct, including a stomp on Louisville defender [[Elvis Dumervil]]'s leg during the game.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=ncf&id=2283020 Virginia Tech kicks Marcus Vick off football team] The Associated Press, ESPN.com, [[January 6]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref>

== 2006 Chick-fil-A Bowl ==
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
|Name=2006 Chick-fil-A Bowl
|Date=[[December 30]] [[2006]]
|Stadium=[[Georgia Dome]]
|City=[[Atlanta, Georgia]]
|Visitor=[[2006 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]]
|Home=Virginia Tech
|Visitor1=3
|Visitor2=0
|Visitor3=10
|Visitor4=18
|Home1=0
|Home2=21
|Home3=0
|Home4=3
}}
{{main|2006 Chick-fil-A Bowl}}
{{seealso|2006 Virginia Tech Hokies football team}}
[[Image:2006 VT UGA Chick fil A action.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Georgia's offense executes a running play as Virginia Tech defenders run to stop the advance.]]

No. 14 Virginia Tech was invited to the 2006 Chick-fil-A Bowl after a 10&ndash;2 record during the regular season and a second-place finish in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]]. Coming off a 27&ndash;22 defeat at the hands of [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] during the [[2005 ACC Championship Game|inaugural ACC Championship Game]],<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=253370259 Florida State pulls off VaTech upset, clinches BCS berth] The Associated Press, ESPN.com, [[December 4]], [[2005]]. Accessed [[December 17]], [[2007]].</ref> the Hokies were pitted against the [[2005 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]], a tough [[Southeastern Conference]] team that finished 8&ndash;4 during the regular season.<ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/03/AR2006120301091.html "Virginia Tech Will Be Going to the 'Dawgs"] Kilgore, Adam. ''The Washington Post'', E08. [[December 6]] [[2006]]. Accessed [[October 30]] [[2007]].</ref> Thanks to their better record and second-place ACC finish, various casinos and betting organizations favored Virginia Tech by 2.5&ndash;3 points when setting their [[point spread]].<ref>[http://www.1800-sports.com/peach-bowl.shtml "Betting Odds on the Chick-fil-A Bowl<U+2014>Georgia vs. Virginia Tech"], 1800-sports.com, [[December 30]] [[2006]]. Accessed [[November 30]] [[2007]].</ref><ref>[http://www.bodoglife.com/betting-matchups/ncaa-college-football/20061230/7-56 "NCAA College Football Betting Matchup - 7 at 56"] Bodoglife.com, [[December 30]] [[2006]]. Accessed [[November 30]] [[2007]].</ref>

The Hokies lived up to their favored status in the first half, running up a 21-3 lead before [[halftime]],<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=263640259&period=2 2nd Quarter] ESPN.com 2nd Quarter Play-by-Play. Accessed [[October 10]] [[2007]].</ref> thanks in part to a well-executed pass by [[wide receiver]] Eddie Royal on a [[trick play]]. Royal also performed well during [[punt]] and [[kickoff|kick]] returns, putting Virginia Tech in good field position throughout the half. 

During the second half, however, things began to fall apart for Virginia Tech. Hokie quarterback [[Sean Glennon]] threw three [[interception]]s and [[fumble]]d the ball once, giving Georgia excellent field position and many chances to score. Tech clung to a 21&ndash;13 lead at the end of the third quarter,<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=263640259&period=3 3rd Quarter] ESPN.com 3rd Quarter Play-by-Play. Accessed [[October 10]] [[2007]].</ref> but halfway through the fourth quarter, Georgia took a 31&ndash;21 lead over Virginia Tech.<ref name="CFA4th">[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=263640259&period=4 4th Quarter] ESPN.com 4th Quarter Play-by-Play. Accessed [[October 10]], [[2007]].</ref> The Hokies closed the gap to 31&ndash;24 with a late field goal, but Georgia's defense held and the Bulldogs clinched the victory.<ref name="CFA4th"/>

== 2008 Orange Bowl ==
{{NCAAFootballSingleGameHeaderMini
 |Name=2008 Orange Bowl
 |Date=[[January 3]], [[2008]]
 |Visitor=[[2007 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]]
 |Visitor1=7
 |Visitor2=10
 |Visitor3=0
 |Visitor4=7
 |Home=Virginia Tech
 |Home1=0
 |Home2=7
 |Home3=7
 |Home4=7
 |Type=bg
 |Stadium=[[Dolphin Stadium]]
 |Image=[[Image:Orange-Bowl-football-logo.png|150px]]
 |City=[[Miami Gardens, Florida|Miami Gardens]], [[Florida]]
}}
{{main|2008 Orange Bowl}}
{{seealso|2007 Virginia Tech Hokies football team}}

[[Image:KU-VT_Orange_Bowl_Helmets.jpg|left|thumb|250px|[[Bowl Championship Series]] commissioners and the Orange Bowl Committee selected Kansas and Virginia Tech to play in the 2008 Orange Bowl.]]
No. 5 Virginia Tech entered the [[Bowl Championship Series]] (BCS) 2008 Orange Bowl following a successful 11&ndash;2 season that culminated with a 30&ndash;16 win over [[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]] in the [[2007 ACC Championship Game]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=273350103 Hokies ride Glennon's arm, Taylor's legs to ACC crown] ESPN.com, [[December 1]], [[2007]]. Accessed [[December 10]], [[2007]].</ref> The game, which was played on [[January 3]], [[2008]], also featured the No. 8 [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas Jayhawks]], who had finished 11&ndash;1 during the regular season and had been selected via an at-large bid to play in the Orange Bowl.<ref>[http://www2.kusports.com/news/2007/dec/02/ku_play_virginia_tech_orange_bowl_jan_3/?football KU to play Virginia Tech in Orange Bowl on Jan. 3] ''Lawrence Journal-World'', [[December 2]], [[2007]]. Accessed [[December 19]], [[2007]].</ref> Various betting organizations favored Virginia Tech to win the game by 3<U+00BD> points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=750671 |title=Rivals.com Bowl Viewer's Guide |author=Fox, David |accessdate=2007-12-17 |date=2007-12-13 |work=Rivals.com}}</ref>

From the beginning of the game, the Hokies struggled on offense and were held scoreless until well into the second quarter.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=280030259&period=2 2nd Qtr Play-by-Play] ESPN.com, [[January 3]], [[2008]]. Accessed [[January 9]], [[2008]].</ref> Kansas, however, was able to get on the board several times, jumping to a 17&ndash;0 lead before Virginia Tech scored its first points. Kansas's broke the game open in the first quarter after [[All-American]] [[cornerback]] Talib Aqib intercepted a pass by backup Virginia Tech quarterback [[Tyrod Taylor]] and returned the ball 60&nbsp;yards for the game's opening points.<ref>[http://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/content/sports/epaper/2008/01/04/a1c_elmore_0104.html Orange Bowl organizers get it right with Kansas] Charles Elmore, ''Palm Beach Post'', [[January 4]], [[2008]]. Accessed [[January 8]], [[2008]].</ref> 

Early in the second half, Virginia Tech regained much of the game's momentum after wide receiver Justin Harper returned a Kansas punt 84 yards for a touchdown, pulling the Hokies within three points. Tech stopped Kansas's offense on the subsequent possession and drove down the field, seemingly for the tying score.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/playbyplay?gameId=280030259&period=3 3rd Qtr Play-by-Play] ESPN.com, [[January 3]], [[2008]]. Accessed [[January 9]], [[2008]].</ref> Kansas defender Joe Mortensen rushed through the Virginia Tech [[offensive line|line]] and blocked the kick, denying the Hokies three points and preserving a 17&ndash;14 Kansas lead.<ref>[http://www2.ljworld.com/news/2008/jan/04/mortensens_kick_block_proves_huge/ Mortensen<U+2019>s kick block proves huge] Ryan Wood, ''Lawrence Journal-World & News'', Lawrence, Kansas. [[January 4]], [[2008]]. Accessed [[February 14]], [[2008]].</ref> The two teams traded touchdowns during the fourth quarter, but Virginia Tech was unable to get the go-ahead score it needed. Kansas earned the victory, 24&ndash;21, in one of the [[television rating|highest-rated]] bowl games of the 2007&ndash;2008 bowl season.<ref>[http://www.ajc.com/sports/content/sports/stories/2008/01/11/sportbiz_0113.html  BCS ratings strong in Atlanta, lag elsewhere] Tim Taylor, ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'', [[January 13]], [[2008]]. Accessed [[January 13]], [[2008]].</ref>

